<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-10-26T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-10-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="1634" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1634">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.52/682.</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">French
                                        Ambassador</gloss>.</hi><note n="2" xml:id="d1634fn2">The
                                    same, mutatis mutandis, to the British, German, and Italian
                                    Ambassadors; and on October 23 to the Spanish Ambassador (see
                                    under Protection of Spanish interests).</note>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                        <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-10-26">
                                        <hi rend="italic">October 26, 1915</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">My dear Mr. Ambassador</hi>: Referring to
                                previous correspondence in regard to the protection of French
                                interests in Mexico, I beg to <pb facs="1186" n="1070" xml:id="pg_1070"/> inform you that the Department is in receipt
                                of two telegrams from its representative at Torreon, in which he
                                states that the de facto Government of Mexico has informed him that,
                                in matters concerning the interests of foreign governments, it
                                desires to deal directly with accredited representatives of those
                                governments.</p>
                            <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Frank L. Polk.</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>